January through March was the worst quarter for the Dow Jones Industrial Average since 1987

A decline in stocks Tuesday cemented the worst quarter for the Dow Jones Industrial Average since 1987. A table below shows how all 30 components performed from January through March.

On Tuesday, the Dow Jones Industrial Average DJIA, +0.52%  fell 410 points (or 1.8%) to close at 21,917.16. The venerable index was down 23.2% for the first quarter, the biggest decline since the fourth quarter of 1987, when Black Monday (Oct. 19) occurred.

The only Dow stock that rose during the first quarter was Microsoft MSFT, +1.00%, which closed at $157.71 on March 31, up a penny from $157.70 on Dec. 31. (All performance figures in this article exclude dividends.)

The S&P 500 Index SPX, +1.19%  dropped 1.6% on Tuesday for a first-quarter decline of 20%.

The Nasdaq Composite Index COMP, +1.64%  decreased 1% on Tuesday for a first-quarter decline of 14.2%.

